 for bestpractices and # Analytics & Reporting

## Overview
Build a comprehensive Analytics & Reporting system for QuestHabit that tracks product metrics and user events, enforces a sane event schema, and provides both on-demand analytics dashboards and scheduled exports. Integrate with event platforms (Amplitude/GA4) while storing reconciled key events server-side. Ensure privacy controls (PII minimization and opt-out per privacy settings), robust validation, and strict runtime safety for all data handling. Deliver two admin pages (Admin — Analytics & Reports and Admin Dashboard) and ensure seamless integration with the existing project context and design system.

---

## Components to Build

1) Admin — Analytics & Reports (Analytics & Reporting Hub)
- Description: Advanced analytics section featuring cohort analysis, retention curves, funnel/segmentation, ad-hoc dashboards, and exportable reports (CSV/JSON).
- Tech:
  - Frontend: React + TypeScript, with modular components (AnalyticsCard, CohortChart, RetentionChart, ReportTable, ExportButton, ScheduleManager, FilterBar).
  - State: useState<T>([]) for arrays; use derived memoized metrics; ensure null safety on all data.
  - Data Visualization: Reusable chart primitives (bar, line, area) with rounded ends and gradients per design spec.
- Features:
  - Cohort analysis views: acquisition cohorts, retention by cohort, lifetime value by cohort.
  - Retention curves: cohort-based retention curves with interactive hover tooltips.
  - Segmentation: segment by plan, channel, device, country; dynamic filtering.
  - Exports: on-demand CSV/JSON exports and scheduled exports (cron-like scheduler) with status tracking.
  - Scheduling: create, update, pause, and cancel export jobs; notification hooks (webhook/email) if configured.
  - Data sources: reconcile event streams from Supabase (or existing backend) and external trackers (Amplitude/GA4) via a unified API.
  - Privacy: AP/PII minimization per event data; respect privacy settings in reports (redact PII fields).
- Accessibility: keyboard navigable charts, screen-reader friendly labels, sufficient color contrast.

2) Admin Dashboard (High-level Metrics & Quick Actions)
- Description: Admin control panel for top-level metrics, user search, and quick actions.
- Tech:
  - Frontend: Dashboard grid with KPI tiles, recent activity feed, user search panel, quick action buttons.
  - Components: KPIStreakCard, MetricTile, UserSearchPanel, ActionDock (floating quick actions), ActivityPulse.
- Features:
  - Global metrics: daily/weekly active users, ARPU, retention snapshots, event throughput.
  - User search: instant lookup by user ID/email/phone with safe handling of nulls; results rendered as a list with safe map calls.
  - Quick actions: create test users, trigger sample events, export recent data, send notifications.
  - Admin controls: feature flags, privacy settings toggles for reports, audit log access.
- Data: consume unified analytics API; guard all array operations and API responses with Array.isArray checks and data ?? [] defaults.

3) Backend APIs and Data Layer
- Description: Services to collect, curate, and serve analytics data; enforce event schema; provide export endpoints and scheduling.
- Tech:
  - API Routes: REST/GraphQL endpoints for analytics queries, cohort data, retention curves, and export jobs.
  - Database: Tables for events, cohorts, exports, users (or extended user analytics view), privacy settings, and schedules.
  - Event Ingestion: endpoints to tag sources (web/mobile), enforce schema, and deduplicate.
  - Scheduling: job scheduler for exports (with idempotency and retry policy).
- Security: enforce authentication and authorization; scope-based access for admin analytics.

4) Integration Layer
- Description: Connect frontend dashboards with backend analytics services and external event providers.
- Tech:
  - Data Adapters: unify data from Supabase results and external event providers; ensure data safety with data ?? [] and Array.isArray guards.
  - Caching/Performance: memoization for heavy analytics calculations; limit payload sizes; pagination for large cohorts.
  - Telemetry: internal event tagging for usage analytics of the Admin pages.

---

## Implementation Requirements

### Frontend
- Pages
  - /admin/analytics-reports (Admin — Analytics & Reports)
  - /admin/dashboard (Admin Dashboard)
- UI Components
  - AnalyticsCard: generic metric display with value, delta, sparkline.
  - CohortChart: cohort-based heatmap/line visualization with tooltips.
  - RetentionChart: retention curve with hover details and export option.
  - FunnelChart: conversion funnel with segmented filters.
  - ReportTable: paginated, filterable table of exportable reports with status badges.
  - ExportButton: triggers immediate export; shows progress.
  - ScheduleManager: UI to create/update/delete export schedules.
  - FilterBar: persistent filters (date range, cohort, channel, device, country).
  - KPIStreakCard, MetricTile, UserSearchPanel, ActivityPulse, ActionDock, etc.
- Data Handling
  - All arrays guarded: (data ?? []).map(...) and Array.isArray(data) ? data.map(...) : [].
  - State initialization: useState<T[]>([]) for lists; useState<ExportJob[]>([]) for jobs; useState<Report[]>([]) for reports.
  - API responses: validate with const list = Array.isArray(response?.data) ? response.data : [].
  - Optional chaining: safe accesses like event?.source?.type or user?.profile?.email.
  - Form handling: controlled components with validation; show error states without crashing.
- Accessibility & UX
  - Keyboard-first navigation, aria-labels, and screen-reader descriptions for charts.
  - Responsive layouts: single-column on mobile; grid on larger screens.
  - Visual feedback: hover states, micro-interactions for exports and schedule actions.
- Performance
  - Debounce heavy filters; pagination and virtualization for large datasets.
  - Avoid unnecessary re-renders via React.memo and stable callback references.

### Backend
- API Endpoints (examples; adapt to existing routes)
  - GET /api/admin/analytics/cohorts?q={[filters]} -> Cohort data
  - GET /api/admin/analytics/retention?cohortId=&range= -> Retention curves
  - POST /api/admin/exports -> create a new export job (CSV/JSON)
  - GET /api/admin/exports/{jobId} -> export status and result URL
  - GET /api/admin/reports?filters -> ad-hoc reports
  - POST /api/integrations/events -> ingest events with source tagging
  - GET /api/admin/users/search?q= -> user search results
  - PATCH /api/admin/exports/{jobId} -> update export state (pause/resume/cancel)
- Data Models (simplified)
  - events: id, userId, type, name, timestamp, source, properties (JSON), piiFlag (bool)
  - cohorts: id, name, startedAt, users (array of userIds), metrics
  - exports: id, format (csv/json), status (pending/running/completed/failed/cancelled), createdAt, updatedAt, url
  - reports: id, title, filters, createdAt, ownerId
  - privacy_settings: userId, optOutAnalytics (bool), piiAllowed (bool)
- Event Schema Enforcement
  - Validate incoming events against a strict schema; reject invalid shapes with detailed logs.
  - Tag events with source:web/mobile and appVersion/platform when ingesting.
- Export & Scheduling
  - Support on-demand exports and recurring exports (cron-like rules or interval-based).
  - Ensure exports respect data minimization and privacy rules.
- Security
  - JWT/OAuth middleware; admin-only access for analytics routes.
  - Rate limiting for heavy analytics endpoints; audit logs for data access.
- Validation
  - Validate input payloads; default missing arrays using data ?? [].
  - Ensure all array fields are actual arrays before mapping.

### Integration
- Data Flow
  - Frontend calls analytics endpoints to fetch cohorts, retention, and reports.
